<P>
IRELAND BEGINS TOUGH NO-SMOKING CAMPAIGN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DUBLIN, Ireland 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Irish launched a crackdown on smokers Tuesday with offenders fined $150 if 
they break new anti-smoking laws. 
</P>
<P>
Smoking has been banned in theaters, trains, buses, air and ferry ports, 
libraries and schools. Restaurants have been ordered to set up no-smoking 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
The proportion of Irish smokers has dropped from 45% of the population 15 years 
ago to about 27% today, but health authorities are concerned that the rate of 
decline has slowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
