<HEADLINE>
<P>
DARMAN URGES OPTIMISM ON U.S. FUTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM REDBURN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In one of his rare public speeches, Richard G. Darman, director of the White 
House Office of Management and Budget, Tuesday attacked the 
"America-is-in-decline" mood that he said he worries has captured the popular 
imagination in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
"As history seems to be moving America's way, America is less than fully 
conscious of its own continuing primacy," Darman said in a speech delivered at 
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government. "U.S. opinion leaders seem 
less than fully confident of America's vital destiny, its unique capacity to 
move the world toward new frontiers in the 21st Century." 
</P>
<P>
The speech marks an ironic turnabout for Darman, who himself attracted 
widespread attention in the past for his attacks on the self-indulgence of 
American society in the 1980s and implied criticism of certain policies of the 
Ronald Reagan Administration that he helped to carry out. A text of the speech 
was made available by Darman's office here. 
</P>
<P>
This time, while repeating some of his familiar themes, Darman's emphasis was 
much more upbeat, encouraging Americans to be more optimistic about their 
future by overcoming what he called the nation's "fear of flying." 
</P>
<P>
Characteristically indulging his own taste for mixing metaphors from pop 
culture with historical imagery, Darman challenged those he claimed are 
threatening to undermine the American romantic spirit, with its love of 
freedom, distrust of authority and pioneering taste for heroics. 
</P>
<P>
To Darman, one enemy of the American romantic spirit is the "alluring romantic 
image" of the "simple, bucolic, blue-green planet, untainted by competitive 
industrial advance, unmarked by 'artificial' boundaries of competing 
nation-states." The image, he argued, holds a strong appeal to many 
environmental activists. 
</P>
<P>
Darman has emerged as one of the Bush Administration's strongest internal 
skeptics of environmental activism and a harsh critic of Environmental 
Protection Agency head William K. Reilly. While saying that "in the main, 
environmentalism is benign and well-intended," and half-jokingly acknowledging 
that "my wife and children are environmentalists. The President is an 
environmentalist," Darman also argued that it is "a green mask under which 
different faces of politico-economic ideology can hide." 
</P>
<P>
He argued that some environmentalists see the movement as a way to promote an 
anti-growth global management regime that is at odds with the free market, 
progress-oriented approach so popular in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
"Americans did not fight and win the wars of the 20th Century to make the world 
safe for green vegetables," he said. 
</P>
<P>
In a relatively brief discussion of the challenges facing him directly as 
President Bush's budget director, Darman set out his goals for budget 
negotiations with congressional leaders -- talks widely expected to begin soon. 
</P>
<P>
He ticked off several goals, including a reform of the budget process, a 
slowdown in the growth of benefit programs like Medicare, Social Security and 
farm subsidies, an effort to cap the government's hidden liabilities and reform 
of federal accounting controls. 
</P>
<P>
Darman also repeated recent statements that the Bush Administration might go 
along with certain increases in revenues, but stated more clearly that he means 
by that a cut in the capital gains tax and higher user fees rather than any 
rise in income taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DARMAN, RICHARD G; SPEECHES; UNITED STATES; FUTURE; STANDARD OF LIVING; QUALITY 
OF LIFE; DOMESTIC POLICY; POLITICAL ACTIVISM; ENVIRONMENTALISTS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050290-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 212722 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 2, 1990, Wednesday, Home Edition 
