<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY COLLEGE BASEBALL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
IDLE RANCHO SANTIAGO WINS CONFERENCE TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE KRESAL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
HUNTINGTON BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Orange Empire Conference baseball title was supposed to be decided 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
First-place Rancho Santiago and second-place Golden West will still meet, but 
the teams will be playing with nothing on the line. 
</P>
<P>
The title race ended Tuesday afternoon with Rancho Santiago winning it without 
taking the field. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West was defeated by Orange Coast, 12-7, Tuesday at Golden West. 
</P>
<P>
Rancho Santiago (31-8, 17-5 in conference), which had a bye, has a 2 1/2-game 
lead with two games left, thus winning its second conference title in three 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
"This is very nice that we were able to win it with as young a club as we 
have," Rancho Santiago Coach Don Sneddon said. "It was our pitching that really 
did it. We led the conference in ERA (3.38) with a staff that was very 
inexperienced at the start of the season." 
</P>
<P>
Although OCC eliminated Golden West from a chance at first, Golden West had 
already clinched second place and a playoff spot. 
</P>
<P>
The top three teams from the conference will advance to the playoffs, which 
start May 12. 
</P>
<P>
The good news for OCC is that the Pirates avoided being swept in the four 
conference games with local rival Golden West. 
</P>
<P>
The Pirates had 16 hits, including three each by Joe Pence, Steve Hernandez and 
Sid Maldonado. 
</P>
<P>
OCC built an 8-2 lead after three innings, but Golden West rallied to cut the 
lead to 8-5 in the seventh inning. 
</P>
<P>
OCC (16-19, 9-13) scored four runs in the eighth for a 12-5 lead. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Hutchins was hit by a pitch to start the one-out rally. Pence tripled and 
scored on a single by Hernandez. Rod McCall tripled to drive in Hernandez, and 
Maldonado's single scored McCall. 
</P>
<P>
John Douris (4-4) pitched the first 7 1/3 innings, allowing seven runs, five 
earned, for the victory. David Turner (4-3) started for Golden West but allowed 
eight hits and seven runs, five earned, in 2 1/3 innings to take the loss. 
</P>
<P>
Robb Carabba had three hits and Mike Willey and Frank Herman had two hits each 
for Golden West (25-11-1, 15-8). 
</P>
<P>
In other Orange Empire Conference games: 
</P>
<P>
Saddleback 5, Riverside 4 -- Saddleback (13-20, 6-16) had five consecutive hits 
and a sacrifice fly in the sixth inning to score four runs and take a 5-4 lead 
at Riverside. 
</P>
<P>
Brent Ferguson started the winning rally with a single. Jason Thompson and Ted 
Savage singled to load the bases. Tony Wren had a two-run double to cut the 
lead to 4-3 and Neil Carter singled to tie it, 4-4. Brian Hoilman's sacrifice 
fly scored Wren with the winning run. 
</P>
<P>
Corey Giuliano (7-5) got the victory, pitching the first 5 1/3 innings. Pat 
Norville worked the final three innings for the save. 
</P>
<P>
Ben Blomdahl (9-5) pitched nine innings, but took the loss for Riverside 
(26-15, 11-12). 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton 5, Cypress 3 (11 innings) -- Visiting Fullerton (22-13, 12-10) moved 
within a victory of clinching third place. The teams were tied, 2-2, at the end 
of nine innings and each scored in the 10th. 
</P>
<P>
In the 11th, Fullerton's Dave Weckerle doubled and scored on a single by Benny 
Rodriguez. Rodriguez moved to second on a sacrifice by Willy Speakman and 
scored on single by Tom Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Burchit retired Cypress in the 11th for his second save. Tom Kelly (7-3) 
pitched 10 innings for the victory, and Ken Kendrena (4-1) pitched 10-plus 
innings to take the loss. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton had scored in the 10th on an error by Cypress third baseman Doug 
McConathy. Cypress (22-18, 8-14) tied it in the 10th on a single by Mark Pak 
and a two-out triple by Terry Tewell. 
</P>
<P>
ORANGE EMPIRE 
</P>
